Foot-and-mouth disease, Zimbabwe
--------------------------------
Information received on 7 May 2015 from Dr Unesu Hildah Ushewokunze-Obatolu, principal director, Division of Veterinary Field Services, Department of Livestock and Veterinary Services, Harare, Zimbabwe

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 13 Apr 2015
Date of pre-confirmation of the event: 13 Apr 2015
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: June 2013
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: Foot and mouth disease virus
Serotype: not typed
Nature of diagnosis: clinical
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

New outbreaks (5)
Outbreak 1 (Bulawayo peri-urban): Mbokodo, Umguza, Matabeleland North
Date of start of the outbreak: 13 Apr 2015
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 3314 / 84 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: adult cattle in a feedlot and cattle of various age groups from three neighbouring plots.

Outbreak 2 (Harare road): Koce, Umguza, Matabeleland North
Date of start of the outbreak: 13 Apr 2015
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 749 / 2 / 0 / 2 / 0
Affected population: cattle of various age groups in a self-contained commercial farm.

Outbreak 3 (Matobo): Weebit, Matobo, Matabeleland South
Date of start of the outbreak: 14 Apr 2015
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 5000 / 4 / 0 / 2 / 0
Affected population: cattle of various age groups in a self-contained commercial farm.

Outbreak 4 (Nkayi road): Umkiyeni-Kenberg, Umguza, Matabeleland North
Date of start of the outbreak: 16 Apr 2015
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 7136 / 2 / 0 / 2 / 0
Affected population: cattle of various age groups in a self-contained commercial farm.

Outbreak 5 (Figtree): Weldene, Figtree, Mangwe, Matabeleland South
Date of start of the outbreak: 24 Apr 2015
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 396 / 23 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: A herd of 113 feeder steers on pasture, 17 of which had been recently bought at an auction sale in Bulawayo town.

Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 4
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 16 595 / 115 / 0 / 6 / 0
Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]:
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Cattle / 0.69 / 0 / 0 / 0.04
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: illegal movement of animals; contact with infected animal(s) at grazing watering
Epidemiological comments: Infection was first detected during routine farm inspections at Weldene farm in Figtree areas of Matobo district [Matabeleland South]. Weldene farm, a self-contained commercial farm, had, 2 weeks earlier, received animals from an auction sale in Bulawayo city. Trace-back inspections of all properties that had sent animals to this sale were done and revealed infection at one of the source farms in the Bulawayo peri-urban area. Infection was also detected at two neighbouring properties, one of which is Mbokodo feedlot. Mbokodo feedlot also has an abattoir on the same property. Inspection of records revealed cattle originating from Mwenezi district [Masvingo province] in the infected zone that were meant for direct slaughter at Mbokodo abattoir and were illegally diverted into the feedlot and are suspected to have introduced infection into the herd. No other property that had sent cattle to the Bulawayo auction sale had infection. Trace-forward inspections of all properties that received cattle from the auction sale revealed infection at four different sites. All the four infected sites had moved animals out after the date they received cattle from the auction.

Control measures
Measures applied: quarantine; movement control inside the country; screening; zoning; vaccination in response to the outbreak(s); disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s); no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Botswana Vaccine Institute Laboratory (OIE's reference laboratory)/ Cattle / virus isolation / pending

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreaks can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

